{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Amend Section 4A and Section 5 of the Public Order Act 1986",
        "additional_details": "These provisions can criminalise the use of \"abusive\" words or behaviour, but we think the language is vague and overly broad. This can allow for inconsistent enforcement, where individuals may be arrested for words that merely cause offence.\r\n \r\nFreedom of expression is a cornerstone of a democratic society. We think the law as currently written can risk punishing speech that, while perhaps offensive, does not in our view incite violence, serious harassment, or genuine public disorder.\r\n",
        "background": "Amend Section 4A and Section 5 of the Public Order Act 1986 to more clearly define the threshold for criminal liability, limiting it to speech or behaviour that directly incites violence, harassment, or credible threats.",
